Blue-chip stocks rose Tuesday as investors  expected the Federal Reserve to raise short-term interest rates.
The Dow Jones industrial average was up 11.97 points at 3,683.47 at 11:00  a.m. (1500 GMT). Roughly 76 million shares were traded on the New York Stock  Exchange.
Stocks also benefited from a dip in long-term interest rates on the bond  market. Interest rates on the main 30-year Treasury bond averaged 7.42  percent, down from 7.44 percent late Monday.
The Fed's Open Market Committee, which sets US monetary policy for the  coming weeks, was meeting behind closed-doors in Washington. Investors  expected the Fed rate hike to come at 11:30 a.m. (1530 GMT), the typical  timing for such interventions in the markets.
Markets were widely anticipating the Fed to increase the federal funds  rate -- the rate of overnight interbank loans which currently stands at 3.75  percent -- between a quarter to a half percentage point, and the discount  rate, now at 3.5 percent, by a half percentage point.
Hewlett-Packard fell 3/8 to 77-7/8 after reporting a 17.5 percent earnings  increase in the second quarter of its fiscal year.
